    "intro": "Almost every intrusion you will ever investigate touches identity. An attacker who steals a valid credential does not need an exploit, a zero-day, or a dropped payload — they simply log in and look, to your logs, like a legitimate user. That is why authentication is the single most important domain for a SOC analyst to understand deeply. If you cannot read a logon event, tell a Kerberos ticket request apart from an NTLM challenge-response, or recognize when a ticket is encrypted with a weak cipher, you will stare at the exact records that describe a domain compromise and see nothing wrong.\n\nThis lesson demystifies how Windows and Active Directory actually prove who you are. We will start with what Active Directory is — the domain, the domain controller, organizational units, and the forest — using the everyday analogy of a company phone directory bolted onto a building keycard system. Then we will walk through a real logon end to end: how Kerberos issues a Ticket-Granting Ticket (TGT), how service tickets (TGS) get handed out, and why the encryption type on a ticket (RC4 0x17 versus AES 0x12) is one of the highest-signal fields you can look at. We will cover NTLM — the older challenge-response protocol that refuses to die — and why pass-the-hash works. You will learn to read Windows Security events 4624 and 4625, decode LogonType values (2, 3, 10) and SubStatus codes like 0xC000006A and 0xC0000064, and recognize what a normal authentication chain looks like so anomalies jump out.\n\nFinally, we will map the attacks: Kerberoasting (T1558.003), AS-REP roasting (T1558.004), pass-the-hash (T1550.002), and password spraying (T1110.003). For each, you learn not just the indicator but the questions a good analyst asks — Is RC4 normal for this account? Why did fifty accounts fail with 'wrong password' from one source in ninety seconds? By the end you will read authentication logs the way an attacker hopes you cannot: fluently, suspiciously, and fast.",
