      {
        "heading": "How a Logon Really Works: Kerberos",
        "content": "When you sit down at a domain-joined workstation and type your password, you are starting a conversation with the Kerberos Key Distribution Center (KDC), which runs on every domain controller. Kerberos is the default and preferred authentication protocol in modern Active Directory, and understanding its flow is what lets you tell normal logons from ticket-based attacks. The whole design goal of Kerberos is that your password is never sent across the network — instead, it is used to prove identity through encrypted tickets.\n\n### AS-REQ, the TGT, and the TGS\n\nThe flow has three logical steps. First, your workstation sends an **AS-REQ** (Authentication Service Request) to the KDC, pre-authenticated with a timestamp encrypted using a key derived from your password. If the KDC can decrypt that timestamp, it knows you hold the right password, and it replies with a **Ticket-Granting Ticket (TGT)**. The TGT is your master pass for the day — it proves you already authenticated, so you do not have to re-enter your password for every resource. This exchange is logged on the DC as **Event ID 4768** (a Kerberos TGT was requested).\n\nSecond, when you want to reach a specific service — a file share, a SQL server, a web app — your workstation presents the TGT back to the KDC and asks for a **service ticket (TGS)** for that specific service, identified by its Service Principal Name (SPN) like MSSQLSvc/db01.corp.example.com. The KDC issues the TGS, logged as **Event ID 4769** (a Kerberos service ticket was requested). Third, your workstation presents the TGS directly to the target service, which validates it and grants access. The service never has to call back to the DC — the ticket itself is the proof.\n\n### Encryption Types: Why RC4 Is a Red Flag\n\nEvery ticket is encrypted, and the field that tells you how is the **Ticket Encryption Type**. The two values you will see constantly are **0x12 (AES256-CTS-HMAC-SHA1-96)** and **0x17 (RC4-HMAC)**. AES (0x12) is the modern, strong default. RC4 (0x17) is legacy, cryptographically weak, and — critically — offline-crackable. In a healthy modern domain, service ticket requests should overwhelmingly use AES. When you see a 4769 event with **TicketEncryptionType 0x17 (RC4)**, ask why: some legacy applications genuinely require it, but attackers performing Kerberoasting deliberately request RC4-encrypted service tickets precisely because the resulting ticket can be cracked offline to recover the service account's password. So RC4 on a service ticket is not proof of an attack, but it is a question worth asking every single time, and a low-noise field to build a detection around. Pair a spike of RC4 4769 events from one source against many different SPNs, and you are very likely watching Kerberoasting in progress. The analyst's instinct should be: normal for this account, or is someone farming crackable tickets?",
        "codeExample": "// Windows Security Event ID 4769 — Kerberos service ticket requested\n// Note the weak RC4 encryption type (0x17) on a service account SPN — a Kerberoasting red flag\n{\n  \"EventID\": 4769,\n  \"Channel\": \"Security\",\n  \"Computer\": \"DC01.corp.example.com\",\n  \"AccountName\": \"jsmith@CORP.EXAMPLE.COM\",   // the requesting user\n  \"ServiceName\": \"svc-sql\",                    // the targeted service account\n  \"ServiceSid\": \"S-1-5-21-1004336348-1177238915-682003330-4602\",\n  \"TargetServiceName\": \"MSSQLSvc/db01.corp.example.com:1433\", // the SPN\n  \"TicketOptions\": \"0x40810000\",\n  \"TicketEncryptionType\": \"0x17\",              // 0x17 = RC4-HMAC (WEAK). 0x12 = AES256 (normal)\n  \"ClientAddress\": \"::ffff:10.20.5.55\",\n  \"Status\": \"0x0\"                              // 0x0 = success\n}\n// Hunting logic: 4769 where TicketEncryptionType=0x17 AND many distinct TargetServiceName\n// from one AccountName in a short window == likely Kerberoasting (T1558.003)"
      },
      {
        "heading": "NTLM and Why It's Still Around",
        "content": "Kerberos is the preferred protocol, but its older sibling **NTLM (NT LAN Manager)** stubbornly persists in almost every enterprise, and it is the mechanism behind one of the most common lateral-movement techniques you will encounter: pass-the-hash. Understanding NTLM is not optional, because attackers reach for it constantly precisely because it is weaker and, in many environments, less closely monitored.\n\n### The Challenge-Response Dance\n\nNTLM authentication is a three-message challenge-response exchange. The client sends a **NEGOTIATE** message announcing it wants to authenticate. The server replies with a **CHALLENGE** — a random number called a nonce. The client then computes a response by encrypting that challenge using its **NTLM hash** (a one-way transformation of the user's password) and sends back the **AUTHENTICATE** message. The server, or a domain controller acting on its behalf, verifies the response. The crucial detail is what proves identity: **the NTLM hash itself**. The plaintext password is never needed at the moment of authentication — only the hash. This design fact is the seed of the entire pass-the-hash problem.\n\n### Where NTLM Still Shows Up\n\nNTLM appears whenever Kerberos cannot be used. Connecting to a resource by IP address instead of hostname forces NTLM, because Kerberos requires a Service Principal Name tied to a DNS name. Accessing systems in a domain without a proper trust path, older applications, some VPN and proxy authentications, and many scanning or administration tools all fall back to NTLM. On the wire and in logs, successful NTLM authentication produces **Event ID 4624 with an Authentication Package of NTLM** (rather than Kerberos), and the DC that validated it logs **Event ID 4776** (credential validation). A sudden rise in NTLM where you would expect Kerberos — especially to sensitive servers — is worth investigating.\n\n### Pass-the-Hash\n\nHere is the payoff. Because authentication only requires the hash, an attacker who steals a user's NTLM hash from memory (via a tool like Mimikatz reading LSASS) never needs to crack it back to the plaintext password. They can **pass the hash** directly: feed it into their own authentication attempt and impersonate the user across the network. This is **MITRE T1550.002 (Use Alternate Authentication Material: Pass the Hash)**. The signature in logs is subtle — a valid NTLM logon (4624) using an account from an unexpected source workstation, often with LogonType 3 (network) or 9 (NewCredentials), and frequently the same account authenticating from a machine it has never touched before. The questions to ask: does this user normally log on from this host? Is NTLM expected here at all, or should this have been Kerberos? Is a privileged account suddenly authenticating over NTLM from a workstation rather than its usual admin jump box? Pass-the-hash rarely announces itself loudly, so you catch it by knowing what normal looks like and noticing when identity moves in ways the human behind it never would.",
        "codeExample": "// NTLM challenge-response flow (simplified), and the pass-the-hash abuse\n//\n// Legitimate:\n//   1. Client -> Server : NEGOTIATE  (\"I want to authenticate\")\n//   2. Server -> Client : CHALLENGE  (random nonce, e.g. 0x1122334455667788)\n//   3. Client -> Server : AUTHENTICATE (response = f(nonce, NTLM_hash(password)))\n//   4. Server/DC verifies -> logs Event ID 4776 (credential validation)\n//                             Event ID 4624, Authentication Package = NTLM\n//\n// Pass-the-Hash (T1550.002):\n//   Attacker steals NTLM_hash from LSASS memory (never needs the plaintext)\n//   Attacker computes step 3 using the STOLEN hash -> authenticates as the user\n//\n// Log signature to hunt (4624):\n{\n  \"EventID\": 4624,\n  \"LogonType\": 3,                              // network logon\n  \"AuthenticationPackageName\": \"NTLM\",         // NTLM where Kerberos was expected\n  \"TargetUserName\": \"admin-jsmith\",            // privileged account\n  \"WorkstationName\": \"WKS-4471\",               // a host this admin never uses\n  \"IpAddress\": \"10.20.9.31\",\n  \"LogonProcessName\": \"NtLmSsp\"\n}\n// Ask: does admin-jsmith normally log on from WKS-4471? Should this be Kerberos?"
      },
      {
        "heading": "Logon Types and Reading Authentication Logs",
        "content": "The two events you will read more than any others in your SOC career are **4624 (successful logon)** and **4625 (failed logon)**. Fluency here means decoding two fields fast: the **LogonType**, which tells you *how* someone authenticated, and — for failures — the **SubStatus** code, which tells you *why* it failed. Get comfortable with these and you can triage an authentication anomaly in seconds.\n\n### Logon Types That Matter\n\n**LogonType 2 (Interactive)** means someone physically sat at the console and typed credentials, or used a local KVM/RDP console session. On a server, an interactive logon by a normal user is unusual and worth a look. **LogonType 3 (Network)** is by far the most common: it fires when you access a resource over the network — a file share, a printer, an authenticated web app. Most day-to-day 4624 events are Type 3, and both Kerberos service-ticket use and NTLM network authentication land here. **LogonType 10 (RemoteInteractive)** is RDP — a full remote desktop session. Type 10 logons to servers, especially by privileged accounts and especially from unusual source IPs, are prime lateral-movement and hands-on-keyboard indicators. Other values you will meet: **Type 4 (Batch)** for scheduled tasks, **Type 5 (Service)** for service accounts starting services, **Type 7 (Unlock)** for unlocking a workstation, and **Type 9 (NewCredentials)** which appears with runas /netonly and is commonly seen in pass-the-hash and credential-abuse scenarios.\n\n### Reading Failures: SubStatus Codes\n\nA 4625 failed logon carries a **Status** and **SubStatus** code that pinpoints the reason. The two you must memorize: **0xC000006A** means *the username was correct but the password was wrong*, and **0xC0000064** means *the user name does not exist*. That distinction is enormously useful. A burst of 0xC000006A against many different valid usernames is a **password spray** — the attacker knows the accounts exist and is trying one password across all of them. A burst of 0xC0000064 is more like **username enumeration** — the attacker is guessing account names and mostly missing. Other codes worth knowing: **0xC0000234** (account locked out), **0xC0000072** (account disabled), **0xC0000070** (logon from an unauthorized workstation), and **0xC0000193** (account expired).\n\n### What a Normal Chain Looks Like\n\nBuild a mental template of normal so anomalies stand out. A user arriving in the morning typically produces: a **4768** (TGT requested) on a DC, followed by **4769** service ticket requests as they open shares and apps, and **4624 Type 2 or 7** on their own workstation. Network access to servers shows **4624 Type 3** with an **AuthenticationPackage of Kerberos** and an AES encryption type. Failures are occasional, human-paced, and self-correct (a mistyped password, then success). Now contrast the abnormal: fifty 4625s with SubStatus 0xC000006A from one source IP in ninety seconds, or a 4624 Type 10 to a domain controller by a service account, or a run of 4769 events with RC4 encryption against a dozen SPNs. The events themselves are ordinary Windows telemetry — what makes them an incident is the *pattern*, the *rate*, and the *account and source they involve*. Reading logs well is pattern recognition anchored in knowing what a boring Tuesday looks like.",
        "codeExample": "// Windows Security Event ID 4625 — failed logon, password-spray pattern\n// Note SubStatus 0xC000006A (valid user, wrong password) across many accounts from one source\n{\n  \"EventID\": 4625,\n  \"Channel\": \"Security\",\n  \"Computer\": \"DC01.corp.example.com\",\n  \"TargetUserName\": \"agarcia\",                 // varies each event: agarcia, bpatel, cwong...\n  \"TargetDomainName\": \"CORP\",\n  \"LogonType\": 3,                              // network logon attempt\n  \"Status\": \"0xC000006D\",                       // top-level: logon failure\n  \"SubStatus\": \"0xC000006A\",                    // valid username, WRONG PASSWORD (spray)\n  \"IpAddress\": \"185.220.101.47\",               // single external source hitting many users\n  \"WorkstationName\": \"KALI\",\n  \"AuthenticationPackageName\": \"NTLM\"\n}\n// SubStatus decoder for triage:\n//   0xC000006A = wrong password (user exists)   -> spray if many distinct users\n//   0xC0000064 = user does not exist            -> enumeration\n//   0xC0000234 = account locked out\n//   0xC0000072 = account disabled\n//   0xC0000070 = workstation restriction\n// Hunt: count(distinct TargetUserName) by IpAddress within 5m where SubStatus=0xC000006A"
      },
      {
        "heading": "How Attackers Abuse Authentication — and What to Ask",
        "content": "Now we tie the mechanics to the attacks. Four techniques dominate credential-focused intrusions, and each leaves a fingerprint in exactly the fields you just learned to read. For each, the goal is not only to recognize the indicator but to internalize the *question* a strong analyst asks, because indicators produce alerts and questions produce conclusions.\n\n### Kerberoasting (T1558.003)\n\nAny domain user can request a service ticket (4769) for any service account that has a Service Principal Name. The ticket is encrypted with the service account's password hash, so if an attacker requests one — especially in weak **RC4 (0x17)** — they can crack it offline at leisure to recover the service account's plaintext password. Service accounts are juicy because they are often over-privileged and have passwords that rarely change. **The fingerprint:** a spike of 4769 events, TicketEncryptionType 0x17, one requesting account, many distinct high-value SPNs, no corresponding legitimate application activity. **The questions:** Is RC4 normal for these services? Why is one user pulling tickets for a dozen service accounts at once? Does the requesting workstation run anything that would legitimately touch all those services?\n\n### AS-REP Roasting (T1558.004)\n\nSome accounts have 'Do not require Kerberos pre-authentication' enabled. For those accounts, an attacker can request an **AS-REP** (Event ID 4768) without proving they know the password, and part of the reply is encrypted with the account's key — again crackable offline. **The fingerprint:** 4768 requests for accounts flagged as pre-auth-not-required, often in RC4. **The questions:** Which accounts in the domain have pre-authentication disabled, and why? Is anyone requesting AS-REPs for those accounts from an unexpected host?\n\n### Pass-the-Hash (T1550.002)\n\nAs covered earlier: a stolen NTLM hash used directly to authenticate. **The fingerprint:** 4624 Type 3 or Type 9 with AuthenticationPackage NTLM, a privileged or service account authenticating from a workstation it has no business using, often following LSASS access on a source host (which your EDR may flag). **The questions:** Does this account normally originate from this host? Should this connection have been Kerberos? Is there LSASS-access or credential-dumping telemetry on the source machine in the same window?\n\n### Password Spraying (T1110.003)\n\nInstead of many passwords against one account (which triggers lockout), the attacker tries one common password against many accounts. **The fingerprint:** many **4625** events, **SubStatus 0xC000006A**, many distinct TargetUserName values, one or few source IPs, a tight time window, and — the sting in the tail — often a single **4624 success** buried at the end when one weak password finally works. **The questions:** How many distinct users failed from this source? Was there a success afterward? Is the source internal or external, and does anything legitimate authenticate that way? Across all four, one meta-question underpins your judgment: *given who this account is and where it normally works, does this authentication make human sense?* Attacks against identity are quiet because they use real credentials — your edge is that you know the baseline and the credential's owner does not know you are watching how it moves.",
        "codeExample": "// Splunk SPL — four authentication-attack hunts anchored on the fields from this lesson\n\n// 1) Kerberoasting (T1558.003): one user, many SPNs, weak RC4 tickets\nindex=wineventlog EventCode=4769 Ticket_Encryption_Type=0x17\n| stats dc(Service_Name) as unique_spns, values(Service_Name) as spns by Account_Name, Client_Address\n| where unique_spns > 8\n\n// 2) AS-REP Roasting (T1558.004): TGT requests with pre-auth disabled, RC4\n| append [ search index=wineventlog EventCode=4768 Ticket_Encryption_Type=0x17 Pre_Authentication_Type=0\n          | stats count by Account_Name, Client_Address ]\n\n// 3) Pass-the-Hash (T1550.002): NTLM network logon by privileged acct from odd host\n| append [ search index=wineventlog EventCode=4624 Logon_Type=3 Authentication_Package=NTLM Account_Name=admin-*\n          | stats values(Workstation_Name) as src_hosts by Account_Name ]\n\n// 4) Password spray (T1110.003): many distinct users, wrong-password substatus, one source\n| append [ search index=wineventlog EventCode=4625 Sub_Status=0xC000006A\n          | stats dc(Account_Name) as sprayed_users, count as attempts by Source_Network_Address\n          | where sprayed_users > 15 ]"
      }
